include ../../tlMatter.pug
if docLang === "EN"
  mixin tl(tlText)
    if tlText != null
      +inlineTl("EN", tlText)
    else
      +inlineTl("EN")
        block
    
  mixin tlDb(key)
    case key
      when "teidealNaCaibidle"
        | The Initial Mutations
      when "10-title"
        | #[+renderKey("Caibidil", { getFromCommon: true })] 10 | #[+renderKey("teidealNaCaibidle")]
      when "10-1-title"
        | General
      when "10-1-p"
        | An initial mutation is a change made to the beginning of a word due to gender, case, tense or other grammatical circumstances. The initial mutations include lenition, eclipsis, #[i t] before a vowel, #[i t] before #[i s], #[i h] before a vowel and #[i d&rsquo;] before a vowel or before #[i fh&#x2011;]. The use of initial mutations is explained here, including the lenition of an indefinite noun after a feminine noun and the lenition of an indefinite noun after a plural noun ending in a slender consonant.
      when "h2-gp-2-5-title"
        | Lenition
      when "h2-gp-2-5-p"
        | These are the lenitable consonants: #[i b], #[i c], #[i d], #[i f], #[i g], #[i m], #[i p], #[i s] (except for #[i sc-], #[i sf-], #[i sm-], #[i sp-], #[i st-] and #[i sv-]) and #[i t].
      when "10-2-title"
        | Lenition of the Noun
      when "10-2-p"
        | Lenition is applied to the noun in the following contexts.
      when "10-2-1-title"
        | After the Article
      when "10-2-1-p"
        | Lenition is applied to the noun after the article (unless the initial consonant is #[i d], #[i t] or #[i s]) &mdash;
      when "10-2-1-a-p"
        | in the nominative singular feminine, e.g., #[i an chathair] #[+tl the city]; #[i an ghloine] #[+tl the glass]; #[i an fhuascailt] #[+tl the release]:
      when "10-2-1-a-sample-1"
        | #[b The woman] is singing.
      when "10-2-1-a-sample-2"
        | Did he close #[b the window]?
      when "10-2-1-b-p"
        | in the genitive singular masculine, e.g., #[i mac an fhir] #[+tl the man&rsquo;s son]; #[i geata an choláiste] #[+tl the college gate]:
      when "10-2-1-b-sample-1"
        | What happened to #[b the child&rsquo;s] gift after the party?
      when "10-2-1-b-sample-2"
        | I needed to leave before the end #[b of the game].
      when "10-2-1-c-p"
        | in the dative singular, masculine and feminine, in some situations where a preposition takes the article according to the Core System, e.g., #[i den chapall] #[+tl of/off the horse] (see #[+link("./chapter1.html#sec_1_4", "1.4")]), or according to the Lenition System, e.g., #[i ar an chapall] #[+tl on the horse] (see #[+link("./chapter1.html#sec_1_7", "1.7")]):
      when "10-2-1-c-sample-1"
        | She would attract the bird #[b off the tree].
      when "10-2-1-c-sample-2"
        | Additional funding was given #[b to the company].
      when "10-2-2-title"
        | After the Vocative Particle
      when "10-2-2-p"
        | Lenition is applied after the vocative particle in the singular and plural, masculine and feminine, e.g., #[i a dhuine chóir] #[+tl O good man]; #[i a Ghaela!] #[+tl O Gael!]; #[i a chairde na páirte] #[+tl O friends of the party]:
      when "10-2-2-sample-1"
        | #[b O noble people], you are welcome here tonight.
      when "10-2-2-sample-2"
        | Well done, #[b O men]!
      when "10-2-3-title"
        | After Certain Adjectives
      when "10-2-3-p"
        | Lenition is applied to the noun after the following adjectives &mdash;
      when "10-2-3-a-p"
        | the possessive adjectives #[i mo], #[i do], #[i a] (masculine singular), e.g., #[i mo mhac] #[+tl my son]; #[i do theach] #[+tl your house]; #[i a pheann] #[+tl his pen]:
      when "10-2-3-a-sample-1"
        | It is #[b my bag].
      when "10-2-3-a-sample-2"
        | Where did he leave #[b his car]?
      when "10-2-3-b-p"
        | the distributive adjective #[i uile] #[+tl every], e.g., #[i an uile fhocal] #[+tl every word]; #[i gach uile sheachtain] #[+tl every week]:
      when "10-2-3-b-sample-1"
        | #[b Every kind] of person attends it.
      when "10-2-3-b-sample-2"
        | She has seen #[b every episode] in the series.
      when "10-2-3-c-p"
        | the indefinite adjective #[i aon] #[+tl any], e.g., #[i aon mhála] #[+tl one bag], #[i aon chóta] #[+tl one coat] (except when the noun begins with #[i d], #[i t] or #[i s], e.g., #[i aon duine] #[+tl one person], #[i aon teaghlach] #[+tl one family]):
      when "10-2-3-c-sample-1"
        | There was not #[b any food] in the house.
      when "10-2-3-c-sample-2"
        | Did you get #[b any parcels] in the mail?
      when "10-2-4-title"
        | After Certain Numbers
      when "10-2-4-p"
        | Lenition is applied to the noun after the following numbers &mdash;
      when "10-2-4-a-p"
        | the cardinal number #[i aon] #[+tl one] and the ordinal number #[i céad] #[+tl first], unless the initial consonant is #[i d], #[i t] or #[i s], e.g., #[i aon chailín amháin] #[+tl (only) one girl]; #[i an chéad bhróg] #[+tl the first shoe]; #[i aon samhradh amháin] #[+tl one summer]; #[i an chéad teach] #[+tl the first house]:
      when "10-2-4-a-sample-1"
        | There is only #[b one way] to do it.
      when "10-2-4-a-sample-2"
        | That was the #[b first picture] he ever sold.
      when "10-2-4-b-p"
        | #[i dhá] #[+tl two], e.g., #[i dhá chrann] #[+tl two trees]; #[i an dá chóta] #[+tl the two coats]; except when the possessive adjective #[i a] (third person singular feminine and third person plural), #[i ár] #[+tl our] or #[i bhur] #[+tl your] precedes it, e.g., #[i dhá chapall ach a dhá géag] #[+tl two horses but her two legs] (third person singular feminine); #[i ár dhá gcapall] #[+tl our two horses]; #[i bhur dhá dteach] #[+tl your two houses]; #[i a dhá mbó] #[+tl their two cows] (third person plural) (see #[+link("./chapter8.html#sec_8_3_3", "8.3.3")]):
      when "10-2-4-b-sample-1"
        | She was the woman who had #[b two dogs].
      when "10-2-4-b-sample-2"
        | The #[b two projects] are finished now.
      when "10-2-4-c-p"
        | #[i trí] #[+tl three], #[i ceithre] #[+tl four], #[i cúig] #[+tl five], #[i sé] #[+tl six], e.g., #[i trí bhád] #[+tl three boats]; #[i ceithre bhó] #[+tl four cows] (except for nouns that have a special plural form after the cardinal numbers &mdash; see #[+link("./chapter9.html#sec_9_3_2", "9.3.2")], and for the word #[i cent], e.g., #[i dhá cent] #[+tl two cents]; #[i cúig cent] #[+tl five cents]):
      when "10-2-4-c-sample-1"
        | I only sent #[b five Christmas cards] this year.
      when "10-2-4-c-sample-2"
        | She read #[b six chapters] before the class.
      when "10-2-4-note-p"
        | Note:
      when "10-2-4-note-a-i-p"
        | that the initial mutation that applies is that of the final number in a series to be placed before the word it qualifies, e.g., #[i sé nó seacht mbád] #[+tl six or seven boats];
      when "10-2-4-note-a-ii-p"
        | that if the Simplified System above twenty (#[i fiche]) is used (see #[+link("./chapter9.html#sec_9_3_10", "9.3.10")] &mdash; #[+link("./chapter9.html#sec_9_3_12", "9.3.12")]), lenition is not applied to the noun, e.g., #[i fiche a trí capall] #[+tl twenty-three horses]; #[i 56 fuinneog] #[+tl fifty-six windows].
      when "10-2-5-title"
        | After Certain Simple Prepositions
      when "10-2-5-p1"
        | Lenition is applied to the noun after the following simple prepositions &mdash;
      when "10-2-5-a-p1"
        | #[i de], #[i do] (and #[i a] from #[i do], e.g., #[i obair a dhéanamh] #[+tl to do work]), #[i faoi], #[i ionsar], #[i mar], #[i ó], #[i roimh], #[i trí], #[i um], e.g., #[i de Shiobhán] #[+tl of Siobhán]; #[i do bhuachaillí] #[+tl to boys]; #[i faoi bhord] #[+tl under a table]; #[i ionsar Sheán, mar dhuine] #[+tl against Seán, as a person]; #[i ó bhéal] #[+tl from a mouth]:
      when "10-2-5-a-sample-1"
        | She will finish the work #[b before morning].
      when "10-2-5-a-sample-2"
        | It happened #[b by accident].
      when "10-2-5-a-p2"
        | The prepositions #[i do] and #[i de] are shortened to #[i d&rsquo;] before nouns beginning with a vowel or #[i f] + #[i vowel], e.g., #[i d&rsquo;athair Sheáin] #[+tl to Seán&rsquo;s father], #[i d&rsquo;fhoghlaimeoirí Gaeilge] #[+tl to Irish learners]; but this is not done for #[i f] + #[i consonant], e.g., #[i do Fhrancaigh] #[+tl to the French]:
      when "10-2-5-a-sample-3"
        | It is #[b Úna&rsquo;s daughter] to whom I gave the book.
      when "10-2-5-a-sample-4"
        | She did not give me #[b an answer] except to start crying.
      when "10-2-5-note-p"
        | #[i b], #[i m] and #[i p] are not lenited after #[i um], e.g., #[i ordú um praghsanna a chobhsú] #[+tl an order to stabilize prices]; #[i an tÚdarás um Bóithre Náisiúnta] #[+tl the National Roads Authority].
      when "10-2-5-b-p1"
        | #[i ar], e.g., #[i ar bhád] #[+tl on a boat], #[i ar chlé] #[+tl on the left], #[i ar dheis] #[+tl on the right], #[i ar dhaoine] #[+tl on people] (see also #[+link("./chapter10.html#sec_10_6_4_b", "10.6.4(b)")]):
      when "10-2-5-b-sample-1"
        | She does not know how to put a button #[b on a coat].
      when "10-2-5-b-sample-2"
        | He left his shoes #[b on a rock] near the sea.
      when "10-2-5-b-p2"
        | Note that the noun is not lenited for adverbial phrases or verbal nouns indicating state or position, e.g., #[i ar ball] #[+tl a while ago]; #[i ar bord (loinge)] #[+tl on board (ship)]; #[i ar comhaois] #[+tl of same age]; #[i ar comhchéim] #[+tl in step]; #[i ar comhscór] #[+tl in a tie]; #[i ar comhstádas] #[+tl in equal status]; #[i ar deireadh] #[+tl at the end]; #[i ar fad] #[+tl at length]; #[i ar fiar] #[+tl inclined]; #[i ar meisce] #[+tl in drunkenness]; #[i ar muir agus ar tír] #[+tl by land and sea]; #[i ar srian] #[+tl in reins]; #[i ar tiús] #[+tl in thickness]; #[i ar bogadh] #[+tl in loose]; #[i ar crochadh] #[+tl hanging]; #[i ar fáil] #[+tl available]; #[i ar siúl] (meaning #[i happening]); but #[i ar fheabhas] #[+tl excellent]; #[i ar shiúl] (meaning #[i gone]). However, lenition is applied to the noun if it is qualified, e.g., #[i ar chonradh sealadach] #[+tl on a temporary contract]; #[i ar shaoire mháithreachais] #[+tl on maternity leave]; #[i ar bharr an tí] #[+tl on top of the house]; except for #[i ar bord loinge] #[+tl on board a ship]; #[i ar ball beag] #[+tl a little while ago].
      when "10-2-5-c-p1"
        | #[i gan], on an unqualified noun unless the initial consonant is #[i d], #[i t], #[i s] or #[i f], e.g., #[i gan chuid] #[+tl without a part]; #[i gan chiall] #[+tl without sense]; #[i gan mhaith] #[+tl without good]; #[i gan mheabhair] #[+tl without mind]; #[i gan bhréag] #[+tl without a lie]; but #[i gan dearmad] #[+tl without forgetting]; #[i gan sagart] #[+tl without a priest]; #[i gan tine] #[+tl without fire]; #[i gan feoirling] #[+tl without a farthing] (exception: #[i gan fhios] #[+tl without knowledge]);
      when "10-2-5-c-sample-1"
        | The soldiers left the gate open #[b without protection].
      when "10-2-5-c-sample-2"
        | The other members will arrive #[b without delay].
      when "10-2-5-c-p2"
        | Lenition is not applied to a qualified noun, e.g., #[i gan pingin rua] #[+tl without a red penny]; #[i gan carn aoiligh] #[+tl without a heap of lime]; #[i gan bolgán solais] #[+tl without a light bulb]; #[i gan ciall linbh] #[+tl without a child&rsquo;s sense]; #[i gan brí ar bith] #[+tl without any meaning]; #[i gan misneach a chailleadh] #[+tl without losing courage]:
      when "10-2-5-c-sample-3"
        | They were left #[b without a safe harbor].
      when "10-2-5-c-sample-4"
        | They said the process would not be changed #[b without good reason].
      when "10-2-5-c-sample-5"
        | They left #[b without earning a penny].
      when "10-2-5-c-p3"
        | Note that lenition is not applied to an unqualified noun if it is a definite proper name, e.g., #[i d&rsquo;fhág siad gan Cáit] #[+tl they left without Cáit]; or if it is a verbal noun in a noun phrase, e.g., #[i b&rsquo;fhearr duit gan pósadh] #[+tl you would prefer without marrying]; #[i moladh dó gan corraí] #[+tl he was praised without anger]:
      when "10-2-5-c-sample-6"
        | She finished the work #[b without Micheál].
      when "10-2-5-c-sample-7"
        | She decided #[b without surrendering].
      when "10-2-5-d-p1"
        | #[i idir], when it means #[i both], e.g., #[i idir bheag agus mhór] #[+tl both small and large]; #[i idir chailíní agus bhuachaillí] #[+tl both girls and boys]. The noun following #[i idir] is not lenited if it begins with #[i d], #[i t] or #[i s], e.g., #[i idir shúgradh is dáiríre] #[+tl both play and serious]; #[i idir mhná rialta agus sagairt] #[+tl both nuns and priests]:
      when "10-2-5-d-sample-1"
        | There are #[b both words] and #[b pictures] in the book.
      when "10-2-5-d-sample-2"
        | There will be #[b both young people] and #[b seniors] present.
      when "10-2-5-d-p2"
        | Note that lenition is not applied to a noun after #[i idir] when it means #[i between], e.g., #[i idir Corcaigh agus Gaillimh] #[+tl between Cork and Galway]; #[i idir breith agus baisteadh] #[+tl between birth and baptism]; #[i idir tithe] #[+tl between houses]; #[i idir béilí] #[+tl between meals]:
      when "10-2-5-d-sample-3"
        | The child was awake #[b between midnight] and #[b dawn].
      when "10-2-5-d-sample-4"
        | A fight started #[b between two] men outside the shop.
      when "10-2-5-e-p1"
        | #[i thar], e.g., #[i léim sé thar gheata ard] #[+tl he jumped over a high gate]; #[i ní raibh thar chúigear acu ann] #[+tl there were no more than five of them there]:
      when "10-2-5-e-sample-1"
        | It is not worth #[b more than a penny].
      when "10-2-5-e-sample-2"
        | The book is not #[b beyond praise].
      when "10-2-5-e-p2"
        | Note that lenition is not applied to a noun after #[i thar] in certain phrases containing an indefinite noun, e.g., #[i thar barr] #[+tl over the top]; #[i thar bráid] #[+tl over the limit]; #[i thar cionn] #[+tl over the head]; #[i thar fóir] #[+tl over the edge]; #[i thar sáile] #[+tl over the sea]; #[i thar toinn] #[+tl over the waves]; nor in the compound preposition #[i thar ceann] #[+tl for the sake of]:
      when "10-2-5-e-sample-3"
        | They drove her out #[b beyond the country].
      when "10-2-5-e-sample-4"
        | He spent a period #[b overseas] before he started working here.
      when "10-2-5-e-note-p"
        | If a series of nouns is subject to a simple preposition, the initial mutation is applied only to the noun immediately following it, e.g., #[i Rinne siad taighde ar chonarthaí, comhaontuithe, córais agus scéimeanna] #[+tl They conducted research on contracts, agreements, systems, and schemes]; except when #[i idir] is used to mean #[i both], e.g., #[i idir bheag agus mhór] #[+tl both small and large].
      when "10-2-6-title"
        | After Certain Compound Prepositions
      when "10-2-6-p1"
        | A definite noun (see #[+link("./chapter3.html#sec_3_1_2", "3.1.2")]) that is subject to a compound preposition or by #[i cois], #[i dála], #[i fearacht], #[i timpeall], #[i trasna] is lenited, e.g., #[i ar aghaidh dhoras an tséipéil] #[+tl at the front door of the chapel]; #[i cois Bhóthar na hUaimhe] #[+tl by the Road of the Cave]; #[i de bhun mhír (b)] #[+tl under item (b)]; #[i fearacht Sheáin] #[+tl John&rsquo;s ferry]; #[i le haghaidh chlár a ceathair] #[+tl for a four-part plan].
      when "10-2-6-sample-1"
        | She has houses #[b all over Dublin] and #[b Cork city].
      when "10-2-6-sample-2"
        | He said it #[b in the presence of the woman] of the house.
      when "10-2-6-sample-3"
        | It happened #[b around the month] of December.
      when "10-2-6-p2"
        | Note that a definite noun is not lenited after #[i chun], e.g., #[i chun foirgneamh a seacht] #[+tl toward seven buildings]; #[i chun gairdín a gcomharsan] #[+tl toward a neighbor&rsquo;s garden]; #[i chun Meiriceá] #[+tl toward America]; #[i chun Gearóid] #[+tl to Gearóid]; #[i chun Parlaimint na hEorpa] #[+tl to the European Parliament].
      when "10-2-6-p3"
        | Indefinite nouns are not lenited except in established phrases, e.g., #[i tar éis bháis] (meaning #[i after passing away]).
      when "10-2-7-title"
        | After a Feminine Noun
      when "10-2-7-p1"
        | If a (non-definite) noun in the genitive is subject to a singular feminine noun (not in the genitive), it is usually lenited, e.g., #[i cloch shneachta] #[+tl snowflake]; #[i deoir bhainne] #[+tl tear of milk]; #[i gloine bheorach] #[+tl glass of beer]; #[i léine chadáis] #[+tl cotton shirt]; #[i tuarascáil pharlaiminte] #[+tl parliamentary report]; #[i bliain bhisigh] #[+tl leap year]; #[i bliain chánach] #[+tl fiscal year]; #[i bliain mheasúnachta] #[+tl assessment year]; #[i mí ghealaí] #[+tl lunar month]:
      when "10-2-7-sample-1"
        | They went to the #[b football field].
      when "10-2-7-sample-2"
        | Do you play a #[b musical instrument]?
      when "10-2-7-sample-3"
        | Did you finish #[b your homework]?<br />(Lit. #[b your work of home])
      when "10-2-7-sample-4"
        | Stay and drink a #[b glass of cider] with us!
      when "10-2-7-p2"
        | Note that all the contexts in #[+link("#sec_10_2_7_a", "(a)")] to #[+link("#sec_10_2_7_m", "(m)")] list the instances when an indefinite noun subject to a singular feminine noun (not in the genitive) is not lenited. In all other contexts, lenition is applied to an indefinite noun subject to a singular feminine noun (not in the genitive).
      when "10-2-7-note-p"
        | An example could be included in one or more of the following contexts, e.g., #[+link("#sec_10_2_7_b", "(b)")] and #[+link("#sec_10_2_7_e", "(e)")] apply to the example #[i léim fia] #[+tl deer leap].
      when "10-2-7-a-p"
        | The second noun is not lenited if the first noun ends in #[i d], #[i n], #[i t], #[i l] or #[i s] and the second noun begins with #[i d], #[i t] or #[i s], e.g., #[i áit dúchais] #[+tl place of origin]; #[i bean tí] #[+tl housewife]; #[i cúis dóchais] #[+tl cause of hope]; #[i maidin samhraidh] #[+tl summer morning]; #[i saighead draíochta] #[+tl magic arrow]; #[i scoil samhraidh] #[+tl summer school]:
      when "10-2-7-a-sample-1"
        | She is working in the #[b research laboratory].
      when "10-2-7-a-sample-2"
        | The defender was charged in the #[b District Court].
      when "10-2-7-b-p1"
        | The second noun is not lenited if that noun begins with #[i f], e.g., #[i buile feirge] #[+tl fit of anger]; #[i cúirt filíochta] #[+tl poetry court]; #[i deoch fuisce] #[+tl whiskey drink]; #[i deoir fola] #[+tl tear of blood]; #[i pailin féir] #[+tl grass pollen]; #[i sochaí faisnéise] #[+tl information society]:
      when "10-2-7-b-sample-1"
        | The club organized a #[b poetry night] as part of the festival.
      when "10-2-7-b-sample-2"
        | He doesn&rsquo;t have much experience with #[b information technology].
      when "10-2-7-b-p2"
        | Note that #[i beirt] and #[i dís] are exceptions, and lenition is applied to a noun beginning with #[i f] after them, e.g., #[i beirt fheirmeoirí] #[+tl two farmers]; #[i dís fhear] #[+tl two men].
      when "10-2-7-c-p1"
        | The second noun is not lenited if it is in the genitive plural, e.g., #[i rásaíocht gluaisrothar] #[+tl motorcycle(s) racing]; #[i saithe beach] #[+tl beach huts]; #[i scoil cailíní] #[+tl girls&rsquo; school]; #[i scuaine gasúr] #[+tl boys&rsquo; queue]; #[i sraith giorrúchán] #[+tl series of abbreviations]; #[i táin bó] #[+tl cattle driving]; #[i traein paisinéirí] #[+tl passenger(s&rsquo;) train]:
      when "10-2-7-c-sample-1"
        | They wanted to establish a #[b boys&rsquo; school] in that building.
      when "10-2-7-c-sample-2"
        | There was a three-mile #[b queue of cars] in the traffic jam.
      when "10-2-7-c-p2"
        | Note that #[i beirt] and #[i dís] are exceptions, and lenition is applied to a noun in the genitive plural after them, e.g., #[i beirt bhan] #[+tl two women]; #[i dís bhreithiúna] #[+tl two judges]; and that the phrase #[i clann mhac] #[+tl family of sons] is also an exception.
      when "10-2-7-d-p"
        | The second noun is not lenited if the first noun has an indefinite quantitative meaning, e.g., #[i breis bainne] #[+tl excess of milk]; #[i díobháil céille] #[+tl lack of sense]; #[i easpa tobac] #[+tl lack of tobacco]; #[i iomarca cainte] #[+tl excess of talk]; #[i roinnt cáise] #[+tl some cheese]:
      when "10-2-7-d-sample-1"
